name: pentylenetetrazole
Reason: The base unit for comparison could be pyrazole, which has a melting point of approximately 70°C. The pentylenetetrazole contains a pentylene (five-carbon alkyl) group and an additional tetrazole ring compared to pyrazole. Each carbon in the alkyl chain typically increases melting point by 20-30°C due to increased van der Waals forces. However, this effect may be lessened due to the flexibility of the chain, leading to a less ordered solid and lower melting point. The introduction of a tetrazole ring could potentially increase the melting point due to the increase in rigidity of the molecule and potential for hydrogen bonding, usually contributing around 80-100°C to the melting point. However, these effects will have to be moderated due to the competing influences of the flexible pentylene chain.
